<p><strong>Deception</strong></p>

<p>Examples of me using it:</p>

<p>Examples of me facing it:</p>

<p>What should be done:
Ask the other party probing questions to find out what they did for the other companies. What terms did they agree to? How large was their order? Get as many details as possible about what theyâ€™ve done for them in the past.
Never trust. â€œIf I told you I have money in my bank account and Iâ€™d pay you laterâ€, would you sell me the item based on trust? Itâ€™s not about trust.â€</p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Dubious Intentions</strong></p>

<p>Examples of me using it:</p>

<p>Examples of me facing it:</p>

<p>What should be done: 
Build compliance features in the agreement itself
â€œAre you certain your client will pay?â€
â€œOf courseâ€
â€œA hundred percent certain?â€
â€œYes, I am a hundred percent certainâ€
â€œThen you wonâ€™t mind a contingent agreement. Your client will pay for child support. If, for some inexplicable reason which you estimate at 0% probability, he misses two payments, my client will get equity in the houseâ€</p>

<p><strong>Hardhearted Partner/Missing Persons/Ambiguous Authority</strong></p>

<p>Generic Examples:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>â€œIts a perfectly reasonable request. But my wife refuses to go with itâ€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Examples of me using it: Saying â€œI will ask Dadâ€ in property talks
Examples of me facing it:
What should be done:
The keys to countering this tactic are finding out who makes decisions and arranging a way to meet with them. It is important, when possible, to start negotiating with the individual who has final authority in order to prevent this tactic from being used. Try to find out what standards are used to determine whether an agreement will be authorized or not. Prior to negotiating, attempt to find out who makes final decisions regarding delivery times, price, payment terms, etc. You can also ask to set up a meeting with that person if the other party attempts to use this tactic.  Get them to agree in principle, if possible in writing, and then talk to the hardhearted partner. â€œItâ€™s a perfectly reasonable request, I agree, but my wife refuses to go along with itâ€.</p>

<p>Insist on reciprocity â€œAlright, we will treat this as a joint draft to which neither side is committed. You discuss with your boss and I will see if I want any changes which I would suggest tomorrowâ€</p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Creating Stress (by Physical Environment, e.g.)</strong></p>

<p>Examples of me using it:</p>

<p>Examples of me facing it:</p>

<p>What should be done: 
Identity the problem, raise it , and attempt to change it in an objective and principled fashion</p>

<p>Personal Attacks (e.g. Commenting on appearance, attack status by making you wait or interrupting you , not make eye contact or refuse to listen , make you repeat etc.)</p>

<p>Examples of me using it:</p>

<p>Examples of me facing it:</p>

<p>What should be done: 
Recognise it and bring it up to prevent from recurring. 
When youâ€™re attacked in a negotiation, pause and avoid angry emotional reactions. Instead, ask your counterpart a calibrated question.  Set boundaries, and learn to take a punch or punch back, without anger. The guy across the table is not the problem; the situation is. Â There is always a team on the other side. If you are not influencing those behind the table, you are vulnerable.â€Â </p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Good Guy/Bad Guy</strong></p>

<p>Examples of me using it:
Buying pants for Manan in Iceland</p>

<p>Examples of me facing it:</p>

<p>What should be done: 
Ask the principle behind it. Why do you think it is a fair price?</p>

<hr />

<p><strong>Threats</strong></p>

<p>Examples of me using it:
Buying pants for Manan in Iceland</p>

<p>Examples of me facing it:</p>

<p>What should be done:</p>

<p>Threats require credible communication, so if you could interfere with that: ignore it, treat it as if spoken in haste, or spoken with unauthorised authority. Best: make it risky to communicate threats. â€œYour voice is being recorded. What number are you calling?â€
Warnings are much more legitimate than threats. â€œShould we fail to reach the agreement, it seems highly probable to me that the news media would insist on publishing the whole sordid story. In a matter of this much public interest, I donâ€™t see how we could suppress information.â€</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>The first time Steve Jobs fired Andrea Cunningham, he called her into his conference room where he was seated with his â€œCFOâ€ and told Andrea Cunningham â€œIâ€™m going to cut off my contract with you. I think the work youâ€™re doing is terrible and weâ€™re just going to stop it right now so thatâ€™s it, youâ€™re fired.â€
He owed her $35,000 for her services which When Andy Cunningham demanded, Steve Jobs wasnâ€™t ready to pay because he believed her work wasnâ€™t worth it. So after being declined the payment, Andrea Cunningham called up her Mentor (Regis McKenna) and complained about Steve Jobs not paying her The money he owes her to which her mentor (Regis McKenna) replies â€œWell, if you want to get paid by Steve Jobs youâ€™re going to have to have something over him.â€
At that point Cunningham was confused and didnâ€™t understand what Regis McKenna meant, Regis McKenna later cleared the doubt by Letting her know her contacts with the business press was her upper hand against Steve Jobs. She goes back to Steve Jobs and demands her 35000$ later to which Steve Jobs replies â€œWhy?â€
She answers with â€œWell, just so you know Steve I get about 30 or 40 phone calls a week from the business press that weâ€™ve made relationships over the last couple of years asking me what kind of a guy you are to work with and I currently tell them very nice things.â€
After hearing this Steve Jobs Writes her a check and hires her Back Immediately.</p>
</blockquote>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rArzMrhTxF8">Saul Goodman Makes Jesse Pinkmanâ€™s Parents an Offer They Canâ€™t Refuse</a></li>
</ul>

