<h2 id="case-study-salary-negotiation">Case Study: Salary Negotiation</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Use Round Numbers
Assuming youâ€™ve done your homework on whatÂ industryÂ standards are and what value you bring and how much you think you should be making, itâ€™s ok to start with a salary number. But donâ€™t say $100,000. Say, $103,500. Something specific. This shows youâ€™ve done the work. Make sure you can back it up to get to that number. Round numbers are negotiated. Specific numbers, backed up by evidence, are not negotiated.</li>
</ul>

<p>A few general principles:</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>It is VERY hard to advocate for yourself or talk about money, especially if you donâ€™t come from money. Please, please: Do it anyway. You are valuable to your employer. Anybody can be replaced, but doing so is expensive and disruptive. They want to keep you. If theyâ€™re offering to hire you, they probably had a long job search process and really want it to come to a satisfactory conclusion for all of you, YOU included.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>There is ALWAYS more money. If you get a job offer, thank them (profusely is fine), ask to get details of the offer in writing (itâ€™s hard to think clearly about dental plans during a high-stakes conversation), and say you will get back to them soon.</p>
  </li>
  <li>Do not accept any offer immediately, no matter how great it sounds. The best negotiation I ever had was when I said, â€œlet me think about itâ€. And then waiting. And really thinking about it. Making my list. Doing due diligence. Really thinking if there are other offers. Or potential offers.
  Your value on the job market works like value on every other market: supply and demand. Really determine what the supply is for your services and if you can potentially be in demand.
  When you first get interest in being made an offer, you have to determine immediately what the supply is. If supply is zero, you put yourself in a bad position.
  But regardless, you can act like supply is great by being patient and saying first, â€œLet me go over all of this. Itâ€™s a lot to take in. Iâ€™m really grateful for the offer. How about we talk in a day or so.â€Â 
  Trust me: this is a scary thing to say but it has worked for me at least three different times and I was scared to death each time.
  If you are offered a job in the morning, say,
    <blockquote>
      <p>â€œThis is great. Let me go over it and figure outÂ logisticsÂ and family issues and call you back later.â€ 
  Then SLEEP. Then call back as late in the day as possible to negotiate.</p>
    </blockquote>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Talk to people about the offer. Itâ€™s awkward to talk about money, but ask people with experience in your industry if they would be willing to help you evaluate the offer. It doesnâ€™t have to be a close friend, just someone you respect. Itâ€™s flattering and interesting to be asked for career advice, and most people are happy to give it.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Asymmetrical information depresses wages and keeps people stuck in unhappy jobs. To negotiate an offer, say you admire the work and mission of your potential employer and would love to work there, but your only hesitation is the compensation package. Then itâ€™s up to them. There is more money, and they will find it for you. If it doesnâ€™t seem like enough more money, say that youâ€™re very grateful for the new offer but would like to know if itâ€™s possible to go higher. Remind them of your dedication and enthusiasm for the job.</p>
  </li>
  <li>You donâ€™t need to have a reason why you need a higher salary (you donâ€™t have to say youâ€™re paying off student loans, for instance). BUT, if you are changing jobs and this would be a salary cut, you can let them know that.
In some cases a salary cut is the right thing to do â€“ if you would have more autonomy or potential for career advancement or just plain more FUN at the new position, take the salary cut if you can afford it. (I did so once and it was the absolute right decision.)</li>
</ul>

<p>Make them see your point of view and give them the illusion of control:</p>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œIf you were me being offered this job, what would you ask for?â€</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œYou guys are the experts on how one can grow and flourish and bring the most value to your company. What should I ask for and how do you see me growing in the company? Can we outline that out?â€</p>
</blockquote>

<blockquote>
  <p>â€œBecause I like this company a lot and want to accept this, I trust that you will help me figure out the right things to ask for here. Is there anything Iâ€™m missing?â€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>People Donâ€™t Ask â€œHow?â€</p>

<p>If they offer too little or no moving expenses or no vacation or no path to promotion, simply ask: â€œHow?â€.</p>

<p>Insist on objective criteria:</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>Other people in the industry are making $X. I know that I offer $Y in value. Can you walk me through how I can accept $Z that you are offering?â€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>They will keep talking and the numbers will change. Trust me on this.</p>

<p>If you ask for something and they say, â€œWe canâ€™t. This is HR guidelinesâ€. Say,</p>
<blockquote>
  <p>â€œHmmm, are you guys powerless to do anything about this?â€</p>
</blockquote>

<p>Nobody wants to feel powerless. They will make changes or work this through HR.</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>If your potential new employer says they donâ€™t have more money and explains WHY â€“ maybe theyâ€™re small or have a narrow pay band or whatever â€“ that establishes that they are being honest and open with you, which is itself a job benefit. You want to work with people you trust.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>You may be able to negotiate other things rather than pay â€“ working remotely, more vacation, career development, etc. Itâ€™s not all about the money.
But it IS ALSO ABOUT THE MONEY. And it is right and good and proper for you to ask for more money.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Okay, so, if youâ€™re in a job and want a raise or promotion, keep a Brag Book. Write down everything youâ€™ve done, even minor stuff, that was a success or helped your employer or other employees or showed initiative or made money or added to your employerâ€™s reach or prestige.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Do NOT assume your boss knows about your achievements. Bosses are idiots much of the time. (I am a boss, I am often an idiot.) During performance reviews and especially when youâ€™re asking for a raise, list specific examples of your contributions.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>If youâ€™re asking for a promotion â€“ and really, isnâ€™t it time you got a promotion? â€“ highlight how what youâ€™ve been doing goes beyond your current job description and is work that is often done by people in X other (higher-paid) positions.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>These are difficult discussions. Print out your Brag Book list to help you remember things. If you get flustered, itâ€™s fine to ask to continue the conversation later, or ask for a moment to collect your thoughts. Or offer to send your request in writing.
Even if you donâ€™t get a raise or promotion this time, it tells your boss that you expect to be recognized for your work. Itâ€™s a process. Asking for more doesnâ€™t make you look greedy, it makes you look ambitious and eager for new opportunities.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Itâ€™s not just about money. Think of every aspect in a situation. Everything you would like. Then you can give up the nickels for the dimes if your list is longer .Â For instance, one side might just be negotiating salary. But the other side could be negotiating salary, title, insurance, vacation, promotion standards, outside work, etc. The longer list always wins.</p>
  </li>
</ul>

